originalText.text:
Parked there for 8-days for taking a cruise trip.
Good: Staff are professionally behave, dropoff and pickup are smooth. Keep the receipts and follow the instruction for pickup.

Need Improvement: Put a big Parking sign outside, label the elevator and the access door on the street for easy to get in and get out the garage.

originalText.text:
Oh my God! First time trying to park here. This can't be real! I'm a tenant in the adjacent building and we were told we get a discount on parking at this garage.

I tried to park just now. I was quoted the standard rate as advertised in the sign outside. Not a discount rate.

When I asked about the tenant discount he said yes, and kept quoting me the original rate.

I told him I was told otherwise.  Mind you it was really difficult to have a conversation as everything this man said, he yelled at me while acting incredibly impatient so that I felt rushed.

I told him again that I was told tenants get a discounted rate and that if that weren't the case if park elsewhere. He just looked blankly at me as he didn't understand what I was saying.

So I told him that if my building was mistaken about the discount then I dont want to park here.

Then he just yelled at me "Nine dollars!"

What, nine dollars to leave?

I told him "No. I'm not parking here."

Then he angrily waved me forward, into an area with many signs marked "exit". Which exit sign do I follow?

Then some guy comes out and looks at me incredulously as if to say "What are you doing in here???" I wasn't supposed to go this way I suppose so the man insist on turning my car around for me. So I let him in my car which he drives WITH NO CARE WHATSOEVER back to where I started.

Listen. This isn't "Let's Make A Deal". This isn't money laundering. I'm not trying to pull one over on someone.

I just want a coherent answer to my question. Either "Yes, the discounted rate is X" or "Sorry, what you were told is incorrect. We dont have discounted parking for tenants."

Of course when I called the number hoping to get a straight answer, it rang and rang but no answer. After a few tries to call back the same guy answers. When he recognized my voice and/or my question he said "Blue Honda? WE'RE FULL!"

I've now spent 20 minutes calling back again and again hoping to either get an answer or at least annoy the piss out of these jerks.

Who is running this business? Because your employees hate their jobs, hate their customers, and apparently they hate their boss.

UPDATE:

You can see the company's response below to my review.

Here's what this tells me about the company.

Saying "there has been a miscommunication" is a subtle way of deflecting responsibility (even if o my publicly so as to save face).

What WORKS? What would work in this situation would be to say "It sounds like we might have miscommunicated to someone. Could you put us in touch with the party that have you this information? Perhaps we can reach out to clear things up."

What this also tells me is that they aren't sorry.

"We apologize for the experience you had, however..."

It the word HOWEVER that is of importantance here.

Take note - this is a form of victim blaming.  "I'm sorry this happened to you, BUT... here's why it happened to you, and that wasn't out fault."

The only appropriate response to my review would be to say "Regardless of the misinformation, you should never be spoken to in that way. Not by our staff. Not by anyone. Please contact so-and-so and we will work to make this right."

To be clear, the staff was outright hostile towards me. And why? Because I had a yes or no question.

All your staff needed to say was "I'm sorry. I'm not sure why you were told that. We do not offer discounted parking for tenants" and I could have been on my way.

Another thing that isn't addressed in the company's response -- your staff's attempt to charge me $9 NOT to park there. In other words, and attempt to intimidate me into paying $9 for them to let me out.

This is a practice I know to be illegitimate, because when I didn't stand for it, the guy backed down and just let me go.

Lastly, based on the company's kurt reply, I get what's going on here.  They don't HAVE to car about the customer experience. They undercut their competition across the street by offering 12 hour early bird parking for half what the other garage causes.

And in return? Both you and your car handled roughly.

originalText.text: Parker beware!  I have parked here many times and was my go to garage for a great all day deal in NYC.  Unfortuntely that love has turned to hate.  I picked up my car yesterday in the dimly lit garage, did a walk around and didn’t notice anything funny.  Woke up this morning to find scratches all along the back driver side of my car with yellow markings which I know came from the garage.  My car is brand new not a scratch on it and only drive occasionally (8k on it) and rarely to the city (for this reason).  I did notice the attendants do fly around the garage and probably carelessly hit one of the barriers without noticing.  I called right away to be greeted by what claimed to be the manager and told me too bad I should have noticed when I left and nothing would be done and hung up on me. Where did I go between 6pm and 7am this morning?  No where!  And there was nothing on my ticket noting any damage prior to parking.  Please heed my warning and while the price is enticing you will end up paying more in damages.  Let the photos speak for themselves.
